{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a549ed67-e3a9-45fe-9783-a0d03d7a9ee1","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical transition order:**\n\n| Scenario | Events |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created → Activated` |\n| App goes to background | `Deactivated → Stopped` |\n| App returns to foreground | `Resumed → Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying` |\n\n> **Note:** `Backgrounding` is iOS/Mac Catalyst only — use it to save state before the OS may terminate your app. On Android/Windows it won't fire.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2c412d3f-b37d-4ff5-8733-fa0c639f4ee3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development - I can answer this directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":423,"requestId":"081F:1F45CF:A72011:C0D98C:69F2A846"},"id":"342f94d4-0e63-4b11-80a5-ce3a795f1ac6","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:54:39.723Z","parentId":"d12652c3-c8bc-4765-8bf6-04eaf5b42fb4"}
